'Structured logging http for GCFv2


**To run sample:**
1)  You will need to create a pubsub topic to test this sample. 
`gcloud pubsub topics create YOUR_TOPIC_NAME `

1) Execute below commands in either local terminal or cloud shell.
```
npm i
gcloud beta functions deploy nodejs-pubsub-function --gen2 --runtime nodejs16 --trigger-topic YOUR_TOPIC_NAME --entry-point structuredLoggingEvent --source . --project YOUR_PROJ
```

2) After successful deployment, trigger the function w/ empty message.
`gcloud pubsub topics publish my-logging-topic --message=""`

3) Open up logs and verify `Hello, world!` has logged and that you are able to see something similar to below.

![Screen Shot 2022-04-11 at 9 53 23 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331216/162791705-56aa972d-d663-43ed-9fc3-0f1f2295e224.png)


4) Run unit test via `npm run test`

```
npm i
gcloud beta functions deploy nodejs-pubsub-function --gen2 --runtime nodejs16 --trigger-topic YOUR_TOPIC_NAME --entry-point structuredLoggingEvent --source . --project YOUR_PROJ
```

2) After successful deployment, trigger the function w/ empty message.
`gcloud pubsub topics publish my-logging-topic --message=""`

3) Open up logs and verify `Hello, world!` has logged and that you are able to see something similar to below.

![Screen Shot 2022-04-11 at 9 53 23 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331216/162791705-56aa972d-d663-43ed-9fc3-0f1f2295e224.png)


4) Run unit test via `npm run test`

**To run sample:**
1)  You will need to create a pubsub topic to test this sample.

1) Execute below commands in either local terminal or cloud shell.
```
npm i
gcloud beta functions deploy nodejs-pubsub-function --gen2 --runtime nodejs16 --trigger-topic YOUR_TOPIC_NAME --entry-point structuredLoggingEvent --source . --project YOUR_PROJ
```

2) After successful deployment, trigger the function w/ empty message.
`gcloud pubsub topics publish my-logging-topic --message=""`

3) Open up logs and verify `Hello, world!` has logged and that you are able to see something similar to below.

**To run sample:**
1)  You will need to create a pubsub topic to test this sample. 
`gcloud pubsub topics create YOUR_TOPIC_NAME `

1) Execute below commands in either local terminal or cloud shell.
```
npm i
gcloud beta functions deploy nodejs-pubsub-function --gen2 --runtime nodejs16 --trigger-topic YOUR_TOPIC_NAME --entry-point structuredLoggingEvent --source . --project YOUR_PROJ
```

2) After successful deployment, trigger the function w/ empty message.
`gcloud pubsub topics publish my-logging-topic --message=""`

3) Open up logs and verify `Hello, world!` has logged and that you are able to see something similar to below.

![Screen Shot 2022-04-11 at 9 53 23 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331216/162791705-56aa972d-d663-43ed-9fc3-0f1f2295e224.png)


4) Run unit test via `npm run test`

1)  You will need to create a pubsub topic to test this sample.

```

**To run sample:**

1) Execute below commands in either local terminal or cloud shell.
```
npm i

2) After successful deployment, either curl or open the generated http function url in a new browser.

3) Open up logs and verify `Hello, world!` has logged and that you are able to see something similar to below.

**To run sample:**

1) Execute below commands in either local terminal or cloud shell.
```
npm i
gcloud beta functions deploy nodejs-http-function --gen2 --runtime nodejs16 --trigger-http --entry-point structuredLogging --source . --project YOUR_PROJ --allow-unauthenticated
```

2) After successful deployment, either curl or open the generated http function url in a new browser.

3) Open up logs and verify `Hello, world!` has logged and that you are able to see something similar to below.

![Screen Shot 2022-04-08 at 5 05 08 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331216/162548242-03ca585d-0491-4eab-99a4-640f71855cfe.png)

**To run sample:**

1) Execute below commands in either local terminal or cloud shell.
```
npm i
gcloud beta functions deploy nodejs-http-function --gen2 --runtime nodejs16 --trigger-http --entry-point structuredLogging --source . --project YOUR_PROJ --allow-unauthenticated
```

2) After successful deployment, either curl or open the generated http function url in a new browser.

3) Open up logs and verify `Hello, world!` has logged and that you are able to see something similar to below.

![Screen Shot 2022-04-08 at 5 05 08 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331216/162548242-03ca585d-0491-4eab-99a4-640f71855cfe.png)


4) Run unit test via `npm run test`

**To run sample:**

1) Execute below commands in either local terminal or cloud shell.
```
npm i
gcloud beta functions deploy nodejs-http-function --gen2 --runtime nodejs16 --trigger-http --entry-point structuredLogging --source . --project YOUR_PROJ --allow-unauthenticated
```

2) After successful deployment, either curl or open the generated http function url in a new browser.

3) Open up logs and verify `Hello, world!` has logged and that you are able to see something similar to below.

![Screen Shot 2022-04-08 at 5 05 08 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331216/162548242-03ca585d-0491-4eab-99a4-640f71855cfe.png)


4) Run unit test via `npm run test`

logging http for GCFv2


**To run sample:**
1)  You will need to create a pubsub topic to test this sample. 
`gcloud pubsub topics create YOUR_TOPIC_NAME `

1) Execute below commands in either local terminal or cloud shell.
```
npm i
gcloud beta functions deploy nodejs-pubsub-function --gen2 --runtime nodejs16 --trigger-topic YOUR_TOPIC_NAME --entry-point structuredLoggingEvent --source . --project YOUR_PROJ
```

2) After successful deployment, trigger the function w/ empty message.
`gcloud pubsub topics publish my-logging-topic --message=""`

3) Open up logs and verify `Hello, world!` has logged and that you are able to see something similar to below.

1)  You will need to create a pubsub topic to test this sample.

1) Execute below commands in either local terminal or cloud shell.
```
npm i
gcloud beta functions deploy nodejs-pubsub-function --gen2 --runtime nodejs16 --trigger-topic YOUR_TOPIC_NAME --entry-point structuredLoggingEvent --source . --project YOUR_PROJ
```

2) After successful deployment, trigger the function w/ empty message.
`gcloud pubsub topics publish my-logging-topic --message=""`

3) Open up logs and verify `Hello, world!` has logged and that you are able to see something similar to below.

![Screen Shot 2022-04-11 at 9 53 23 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331216/162791705-56aa972d-d663-43ed-9fc3-0f1f2295e224.png)

**To run sample:**
1)  You will need to create a pubsub topic to test this sample. 
`gcloud pubsub topics create YOUR_TOPIC_NAME `

1) Execute below commands in either local terminal or cloud shell.
```
npm i
gcloud beta functions deploy nodejs-pubsub-function --gen2 --runtime nodejs16 --trigger-topic YOUR_TOPIC_NAME --entry-point structuredLoggingEvent --source . --project YOUR_PROJ
```

2) After successful deployment, trigger the function w/ empty message.
`gcloud pubsub topics publish my-logging-topic --message=""`

3) Open up logs and verify `Hello, world!` has logged and that you are able to see something similar to below.

![Screen Shot 2022-04-11 at 9 53 23 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331216/162791705-56aa972d-d663-43ed-9fc3-0f1f2295e224.png)


4) Run unit test via `GOOGLE_CLOUD_PROJECT=YOUR_PROJ npm run test`

Description

#7342 introduced a change where nox would check for `test_*.py` and `*_test.py` files. Django and IDP-SQL had their tests in `test/`, so this glob didn't find these files, and these tests haven't been run for a bit. 



Outstanding issues with these tests: 

*dynamic PR status update follows*

---


 * Django: Postgres 9.6 EOL

```
Step #6 - "Migrate database": django.db.utils.ProgrammingError: column c.relispartition does not exist
Step #6 - "Migrate database": LINE 3:             CASE WHEN c.relispartition THEN 'p' WHEN c.relki...
Step #6 - "Migrate database": 
```

Debugging seems to indicate this happens on old versions of postgres. [Django 4.0 no longer supports Postgres 9.6](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/4.0/releases/4.0/#dropped-support-for-postgresql-9-6). `test-instance-pg` is Postgres 9.6, which is EOL as of November 2021. 

Suggest creating a newer versioned instance of a postgres testing database (happy to help here where I can).

---

* IDP: Linting issues

```
./middleware.py:31:29: ANN401 Dynamically typed expressions (typing.Any) are disallowed
    def decorated_function(*args: Any, **kwargs: Any) -> Any:
                            ^
./middleware.py:31:42: ANN401 Dynamically typed expressions (typing.Any) are disallowed
    def decorated_function(*args: Any, **kwargs: Any) -> Any:
                                         ^
./middleware.py:31:61: ANN401 Dynamically typed expressions (typing.Any) are disallowed
    def decorated_function(*args: Any, **kwargs: Any) -> Any:
                                                            ^
```

This is being addressed as of v2.9.0 of flake8-annotations. https://github.com/sco1/flake8-annotations/pull/136 

It will require adding `--allow-star-arg-any` to the flake8 call. 

---

{'push_id': 9568601191, 'size': 8, 'distinct_size': 1, 'ref': 'refs/heads/ace-n-patch-2', 'head': '92e09a3456ad7f29112c038e792369a5cb493ee5', 'before': '6e6c25ca63282af2689ccc78eab079ec801c2753', 'commits': [{'sha': '7fd151380d3d058eaa1985c04d0bbcfe328effb7', 'author': {'email': 'muncus@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Marc Dougherty'}, 'message': 'feat(internal/cloudrunci): add support for Cloud Run Jobs for running tests (#2480)

* feat(internal/cloudrunci): CI capabilities for Cloud Run Jobs.

* Avoid Platform objects in RunJobs

RunJobs are only supported on the managed platform, and gcloud CLI does
not have a --platform flag, so existing Platform types would need
changes (as in previous commit).

* Apply suggestions from code review

Co-authored-by: Averi Kitsch <akitsch@google.com>

* Rename RunJob to Job

also switches to inline Job definition in the tests.

* Check for log entries in the jobs e2e test.

* Check region, and reduce log wait time.

By removing the initial wait before log checking, we look to be saving
around 2m off of each test run.

* Actually use ExtraCreateArgs, and add doc about multiple Run() calls.

* Module replacement for testing to use the local path

this permits modifying tests and test code in a single PR.
This commit can be reverted later, but is needed to make tests pass on #2480.

```js
import json

import google.auth
from google.cloud.devtools import cloudbuild_v1

def quickstart():
    """Create and execute a simple Google Cloud Build configuration,
    print the in-progress status and print the completed status."""

    # Authorize the client with Google defaults
    credentials, project_id = google.auth.default()
    client = cloudbuild_v1.services.cloud_build.CloudBuildClient()

    build = cloudbuild_v1.Build()

    # The following build steps will output "hello world"
    # For more information on build configuration, see
    # https://cloud.google.com/build/docs/configuring-builds/create-basic-configuration
    j = json.loads(open('cloudbuild.json').read())
    build.steps = j['steps']
    build.substitutions = j['substitutions']
    build.images = j['images']
    build.options = {"pool": {"name":j['workerPool']}}
    # build.timeout = 3000 # j['timeout']

    operation = client.create_build(project_id='<project id>', build=build)
    # Print the in-progress operation
    print("IN PROGRESS:")
    print(operation.metadata)

    result = operation.result()
    # Print the completed status
    print("RESULT:", result.status)
# [END cloudbuild_quickstart]


if __name__ == "__main__":
    quickstart()
